natural_language: Always if block a is clear then eventually the following disjunction holds: first disjunct is hold a and in the next state block b is clear, second disjunct is block c is on d until block e is on table
expected_ltlf: G(clear(a) -> F((holding(a) & X(clear(b))) | (on(c, d) U ontable(e))))
actual_ltlf: G(clear(a) -> F((((holding(a) & X(clear(b)))) | ((on(c, d) U ontable(e))))))
description: Deep nesting: G -> F -> (conjunction | until) with Next inside
notes: Tests: G, F, &, |, X, U operators with 3-level nesting

natural_language: Eventually the following implication holds: if block a is on b then the following nested implication holds: if block c is clear then always the following disjunction holds: first disjunct is block d is on e, second disjunct is a conjunction where block f is eventually on g and block h is not clear
description: Nested implications with disjunction and negation: F -> (-> (G | (F &)))
notes: Tests: F, ->, G, |, &, ! operators with 4-level nesting and 8 objects

natural_language: The following equivalence holds: on the left side, both holding a, and the state that block b is clear until block c is on d hold; right side is block e stays on table release condition which is a conjunction of eventually block f is on g and always block h is clear
expected_ltlf: (holding(a) & clear(b) U on(c, d)) <-> (ontable(e) R (F(on(f, g)) & G(clear(h))))
actual_ltlf: ((holding(a) & ((clear(b) U on(c, d))))) <-> ((ontable(e) R ((F(on(f, g)) & G(clear(h))))))
description: Equivalence of complex temporal formulas: (& U) <-> (R (F & G))
notes: Tests: U, R, <->, &, F, G with binary temporal operators and equivalence
